Vintage style illustration of a frustrated person sitting at a cluttered desk in a 1950s home office, tangled in an absurdly long copper telephone cable that snakes chaotically through the room and out the window into the distance. The cable loops around furniture, through doorways, and stretches toward a tiny building visible on the horizon representing a telephone exchange. A retro speed gauge on the desk shows a needle stuck in the red "slow" zone. Muted sepia and cream tones with pops of faded teal and rust orange. The scene conveys bureaucratic absurdity and the comedy of trying to get a straight answer about infrastructure limitations. Warm afternoon light filters through venetian blinds casting striped shadows across the scene.
